Feb 9 2009 	Exceeded expectations in many ways	What a wonderful surprise this hotel was. I found it through Expedia and it seemed to have glowing reviews, but I was suspect what the downside might be as I had never been to the area or Chicago before. Getting to the hotel was reasonable from Grand station on the red line subway and was probably a 5-6 minute walk. The area itself is filled with late night hot spots and restaurants, though I feel the younger set (under 35) will be most pleased. The hotel entrance is unusual in that you walk into a lobby with elevators which you must take to a second lobby with the actual front desk. Odd, but possibly an advantage in some ways and keeps the check-in area free of chaos.The hotel service/staff is excellent. very friendly and helpful-although very young for the most part. They seem to try hard and smile whenever you cross their path. The rooms blew me away for value: very nicely appointed with a flat screen TV, king bed with different types of pillows, excellent shower with good hot water and pressure, and very clean. This site lists this as a 2 star hotel, but that's not possible, I'd say 3 at least given the room and decor. My favorite part of the room was that it was quiet-no street noise, no neighbor noise, no noise period (I was on the 19th floor I should point out).The breakfast buffet in the morning was nice as far as hotel buffets go. Some of the options included eggs, sausage, piping hot oatmeal, cereals, English muffins, white and wheat bread, juices, waffles, etc. It would be great if they added hash browns or potatoes-it would have felt complete. In summary: an excellent experience in a hotel that felt very new. I didn't have time to visit the pool or exercise room so I can't comment on it however.Tip: If you're a 20-something try Rockit for late night food and drinks (Warning-it's loud there upstairs) Rock Bottom brewery for craft beer or The House of Blues down the street and Hub 51 below the hotel itself.	
Jan 28 2009 	Great service cute hotel but rooms already showing some wear	If only this hotel wasn't getting such heavy traffic. It's a very cute concept, with rooms similar to a Hyatt Place in design. We had a big king bed and really comfy seating area separated by a desk and frosted glass slidable window-like partition. Loved the wireless internet (also wired, both free); as well as the beverage chiller (like a mini fridge but not quite as cold) and the microwave. But the room lacked storage despite lots and lots of empty floor space in the sleeping area. Oddly our bedroom area was huge, while the sitting area was partitioned off in a small and cramped area next to the door. The hotel size swells 4x on weekends according to the desk clerk, and it shows. Weekend breakfast is mobbed and there aren't enough seats, although the attendants do a terrific job keeping the food stocked. And with groups of 4 and 5 crammed into rooms meant for just one or two, the hotel is showing a surprising amount of wear and tear for being so new. These rooms just weren't designed for heavy traffic, which is a shame because it's otherwise a nice place to stay. Our room had a nasty stain on the floor near the door, a lighter stain on the sectional couch, some peeling laminate on the microwave counter, and a hole in the desk chair's woven back from it hitting the edge of the desk.Weirdly, the hotel doesn't iron its linens (the front desk clerk said they &quot;don't have a presser&quot;), so the sheets, comforter and the decorative thingie on the foot of the bed were a wrinkled mess (not very reassuring to crawl into wrinkled sheets; we just crossed our fingers the linens had been changed since the last guest). The shower (no tub in our room) also didn't look super clean, but front desk assured us this is just a cosmetic problem from the laminating and that it's a problem in all the rooms.The upside: great location, super nice desk staff, free Wi-Fi, and it's sort of sweet to see kids in pajamas at the weekend breakfast, which lent a friendly family feel. But it would be nice to see the rooms better maintained -- and maybe some limits on the number of people the hotel allows in one room, especially since it shares space with the Residence Inn, which is really better suited for quad and quint parties sharing one room. We wold stay here again but it would be nice to see the wear issues addressed.	
